TITLE: Loading and Configuring Google Analytics - JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet uses an immediately-invoked function expression (IIFE) to asynchronously load the Google Analytics 'analytics.js' library. It defines a global 'ga' function, initializes tracking using a specified tracking code, and sends a pageview event. Dependencies include Google Analytics and a valid property ID. No external parameters are required beyond the property ID, with output being analytics data sent to Google servers. All code is standard and may be reused or obfuscated as part of best practices.
SOURCE: https://github.com/marcosmeli/filehelpers/blob/master/Build/adddocs.txt#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
// Analytics
  (function(i,s,o,g,r,a,m){i['GoogleAnalyticsObject']=r;i[r]=i[r]||function(){
  (i[r].q=i[r].q||[]).push(arguments)},i[r].l=1*new Date();a=s.createElement(o),
  m=s.getElementsByTagName(o)[0];a.async=1;a.src=g;m.parentNode.insertBefore(a,m)
  })(window,document,'script','//www.google-analytics.com/analytics.js','ga');

ga('create', 'UA-361500-14', 'auto');
ga('send', 'pageview');
```

TITLE: Initializing Google AdSense Ad Slot - JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This snippet asynchronously loads the Google AdSense script and configures an ad slot within the web page. It uses HTML attributes to specify the ad client, slot, and display format. The JavaScript pushes an empty object to the adsbygoogle queue, instructing the adsbygoogle library to process and render the ad. This requires a valid AdSense account and the appropriate ad client/slot IDs. Inputs are HTML element attributes and no parameters to the push function; output is a rendered ad slot or a blank area if adblockers are present. Limitations include possible content blocking by browser plugins.
SOURCE: https://github.com/marcosmeli/filehelpers/blob/master/Build/adddocs.txt#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: HTML
CODE:
```
<script async src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>
<!-- FileHelpers -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:block"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-0287496280465709"
     data-ad-slot="9377653088"
     data-ad-format="auto"></ins>
<script>
(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script>
```

TITLE: Creating the CustomersTemp Table in SQL
DESCRIPTION: This SQL script checks for the existence of the `CustomersTemp` table within the `dbo` schema and removes it if found. Subsequently, it defines and creates the `CustomersTemp` table with columns detailing customer information such as CustomerID, CompanyName, Contact details, and Address. Note that unlike OrdersTemp, a primary key constraint is not explicitly added in this snippet.
SOURCE: https://github.com/marcosmeli/filehelpers/blob/master/FileHelpers.Tests/Tests/Scripts/Temp Tables.txt#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: sql
CODE:
```
if exists (select * from dbo.sysobjects where id = object_id(N'[dbo].[CustomersTemp]') and OBJECTPROPERTY(id, N'IsUserTable') = 1)
drop table [dbo].[CustomersTemp]
GO

CREATE TABLE [dbo].[CustomersTemp] (
	[CustomerID] [nchar] (5) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NOT NULL ,
	[CompanyName] [nvarchar] (40) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NOT NULL ,
	[ContactName] [nvarchar] (30) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ContactTitle] [nvarchar] (30) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[Address] [nvarchar] (60) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[City] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[Region] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[PostalCode] [nvarchar] (10) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[Country] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[Phone] [nvarchar] (24) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[Fax] [nvarchar] (24) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL 
) ON [PRIMARY]
GO
```

TITLE: Creating the OrdersTemp Table in SQL
DESCRIPTION: This SQL script first checks if the `OrdersTemp` table exists in the `dbo` schema and drops it if it does. It then creates the `OrdersTemp` table with columns for order details (like CustomerID, OrderDate, Shipping information) and finally defines `OrderID` as the clustered primary key.
SOURCE: https://github.com/marcosmeli/filehelpers/blob/master/FileHelpers.Tests/Tests/Scripts/Temp Tables.txt#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: sql
CODE:
```
if exists (select * from dbo.sysobjects where id = object_id(N'[dbo].[OrdersTemp]') and OBJECTPROPERTY(id, N'IsUserTable') = 1)
drop table [dbo].[OrdersTemp]
GO

CREATE TABLE [dbo].[OrdersTemp] (
	[OrderID] [int] IDENTITY (1, 1) NOT NULL ,
	[CustomerID] [nchar] (5) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[EmployeeID] [int] NULL ,
	[OrderDate] [datetime] NULL ,
	[RequiredDate] [datetime] NULL ,
	[ShippedDate] [datetime] NULL ,
	[ShipVia] [int] NULL ,
	[Freight] [money] NULL ,
	[ShipName] [nvarchar] (40) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ShipAddress] [nvarchar] (60) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ShipCity] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ShipRegion] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ShipPostalCode] [nvarchar] (10) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL ,
	[ShipCountry] [nvarchar] (15) COLLATE SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS NULL 
) ON [PRIMARY]
GO

ALTER TABLE [dbo].[OrdersTemp] WITH NOCHECK ADD 
	CONSTRAINT [PK_OrdersTemp] PRIMARY KEY  CLUSTERED 
	(
		[OrderID]
	)  ON [PRIMARY] 
GO
```
